{SECT 0 {PARA 256 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "Basics of Graphing " }}{PARA 
256 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 14 "(number05.mws)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "We have already used the basic plott
ing command sequence" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 256 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "      plot(expression,x=a..b,optional stuff includin
g the range on the dependent variable);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 436 "We have already seen that sometimes
 the key to getting a nice graph involves analyzing the expression to \+
determine the appropriate range of values for x and y.  Here we explor
e some more of MAPLE's plotting features.  First we see how to plot mu
ltiple graphs on the same axes.  The key thing to remember is that \"c
urly braces\", \{    \},  are used to denote a set of objects (without
 regard to the ordering of the objects).  For example, " }{XPPEDIT 18 
0 "\{x^2, x, -x^3\}" "6#<%*$%\"xG\"\"#F%,$*$F%\"\"$!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 
45 "   denotes the set containging the functions " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "x^2
 , x, -x^3" "6%*$%\"xG\"\"#F$,$*$F$\"\"$!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 5 ".    " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 21 "Try the M
APLE command" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 48 "plot(\{x^2-2
,x^2-1,x^2, x^2+1\},x=-5..5,y=-5..25);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 102 "You just asked MAPLE to plot the se
t of all 4 functions all at once. Of course we could name the set M" }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 28 "M:=\{x^2-2,x^2-1,x^2, x^2+1
\};" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 23 "and then simply plot M." }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 25 "plot(M,x=-5..5,y=-5..25);" }
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 86 "MAPLE h
as a sequence generator command that will come in handy.  Try the MAPL
E command" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 19 "seq(x^2+i,i=-2..1);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 97 "Use this with the above plot command \+
to obtain the same 4 graphs. (Note, you can copy and paste.)" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 44 "pl
ot(\{seq(x^2+i,i=-2..1)\},x=-5..5,y=-5..25);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "1.  " }{TEXT 256 61 "Why d
oes the seqence need to be included in the curly braces?" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 27 "Note that the grap
h of     " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "x^2+i" "6#,&*$%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"%\"iGF'" }
{TEXT -1 68 "   eventually is entirely above the x-axis.  Plot the gra
phs of     " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "5*x^3-5*x+i" "6#,(*&\"\"&\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"
\"$F&F&*&F%F&F(F&!\"\"%\"iGF&" }{TEXT -1 49 "   for the values of i = \+
-3, -2, -1, 0, 1,2,3 .  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "
" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "2.  Is it possible to find any value
 of i so that the graph of     " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "5*x^3-5*x+i" "6#,(*&
\"\"&\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F&F&*&F%F&F(F&!\"\"%\"iGF&" }{TEXT -1 35 "   is
 entirely above the x-axis?   " }{TEXT 257 20 "Explain your answer." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 24 "Sketch t
he graph of     " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(x^2-1)/(2*x^3+3*x-2)" "6#*&,&*$%\"x
G\"\"#\"\"\"F(!\"\"F(,(*&F'F(*$F&\"\"$F(F(*&F-F(F&F(F(F'F)F)" }{TEXT 
-1 8 "    .   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "3.  " }{TEXT 
258 34 "Where are the vertical asymptotes?" }{TEXT -1 2 "  " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "4.  " }{TEXT 259 58 "Is the vertical line really
 a part of the graph?  Explain." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 438 "\"Click\" in the vicinity of the graph t
o frame the graph and to obtain a set of \"buttons\" associated with t
he \"style\" of the graph.  Experiment with these \"bottons\" to see h
ow they change the style of the graph.  In the case of our above ratio
nal function, plotting only the data points might be appropriate.  Inc
lude the graph of the same function plotted in this \"points only\" st
yle. (Remember, you can copy and paste the MAPLE command.)" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 70 "In each case below, graph the given set \+
of functions on the same axes." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {XPPEDIT 19 1 "\{k*sin(x), k = -3 .. 3\};" "6
#<$*&%\"kG\"\"\"-%$sinG6#%\"xGF&/F%;,$\"\"$!\"\"F." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 52 "plot(\{seq(k*sin(x),k=-10..10)\},x=-10..10,
y=-10..10);" }}{PARA 13 "" 1 "" {GLPLOT2D 480 480 480 {PLOTDATA 2 "69-
